      "message": "I\u0027m not sure I\u0027d mention static, given that we\u0027re not explaining why, and further that I think this example is confused-to-misleading.\n\nWe usually use static to indicate a function or value is scoped to the file, the opposite of extern, and I like to continue to use it for readability even in situations where it\u0027s implied by constexpr for continuity with the team\u0027s pre-constexpr style and existing code.\n\nBut static inside a function causes function-scoping, not file scoping, and it\u0027s usually a sign we\u0027re doing something that requires one-time thread-safe initialization.  To bring it up here combined with constexpr I think muddies the water more than it clarifies anything.\n\nOn the other hand, these constants would lgtm if they weren\u0027t in a function.",
